---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---
<Layout title="Plate Tectonics, Earthquakes & Volcanoes" description="Plate tectonics, earthquakes, volcanoes, and mineral resources of Peru.">

  <!-- Hero -->
  <section class="bg-gradient-to-br from-red-900 to-stone-900 text-white py-16 px-4">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto text-center">
      <p class="text-red-300 uppercase tracking-widest text-sm mb-2 font-medium">Earth Processes · Week 2</p>
      <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-bold mb-3">Plate Tectonics, Earthquakes & Volcanoes</h1>
      <p class="text-red-100 text-lg max-w-xl mx-auto">Peru sits at the edge of the Nazca Plate — one of the most seismically and volcanically active zones on Earth. The same forces that built the Andes also shaped Peru's economy, culture, and history.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto px-4 py-16 space-y-20">

    <!-- ─── SECTION 1: TECTONIC PLATES ─── -->
    <section>
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-8">
        <div class="bg-red-700 text-white text-xs font-bold px-3 py-1 rounded-full uppercase tracking-wide">Section 1</div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-stone-800">Tectonic Plates & Natural Disasters</h2>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white rounded-2xl border border-stone-100 shadow-sm p-7 mb-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-stone-800 mb-4">Plate Boundaries Near Peru</h3>
        <p class="text-stone-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
          Peru lies directly on the <strong>convergent boundary</strong> between the <strong>Nazca Plate</strong> (oceanic) and the <strong>South American Plate</strong> (continental). The Nazca Plate moves eastward at approximately <strong>7–8 cm per year</strong> and subducts — dives beneath — the South American Plate along the <strong>Peru-Chile Trench</strong>, which runs parallel to the Pacific coastline and reaches depths of up to <strong>8,065 meters</strong> below sea level.
        </p>
        <p class="text-stone-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
          This subduction process is responsible for three of Peru's most defining geographic features: the <strong>Andes mountain range</strong> (built by the collision and uplift of crust), the country's <strong>volcanic arc</strong> (caused by melting of the subducting plate), and Peru's frequent and powerful <strong>earthquakes</strong> (caused by the friction and stress along the plate boundary).
        </p>
        <p class="text-stone-600 leading-relaxed">
          Peru also sits within the <strong>Pacific Ring of Fire</strong> — a 40,000 km horseshoe-shaped zone surrounding the Pacific Ocean where approximately <strong>90% of the world's earthquakes</strong> occur and over 75% of the world's active volcanoes are found.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Disaster types grid -->
      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-5">
        <div class="bg-red-50 border border-red-100 rounded-2xl p-5">
          <h4 class="font-bold text-red-800 mb-2">Earthquakes</h4>
          <p class="text-stone-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">Peru is one of the most seismically active countries on Earth. The subduction of the Nazca Plate creates massive stress along fault lines throughout the country, resulting in thousands of earthquakes per year — most too small to feel, but some catastrophic.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-orange-50 border border-orange-100 rounded-2xl p-5">
          <h4 class="font-bold text-orange-800 mb-2">Volcanoes</h4>
          <p class="text-stone-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">As the Nazca Plate melts at depth, magma rises through the overlying crust, feeding a chain of <strong>84 volcanoes</strong> in southern Peru. Several are currently active, including Ubinas, Sabancaya, and El Misti near the city of Arequipa.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-100 rounded-2xl p-5">
          <h4 class="font-bold text-blue-800 mb-2">Tsunamis</h4>
          <p class="text-stone-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">Large undersea earthquakes along the Peru-Chile Trench can displace massive volumes of water, generating tsunamis. The 1746 Lima earthquake triggered a tsunami that destroyed the port of Callao and killed thousands. Peru has a national tsunami warning system today.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ─── SECTION 2: ROCKS & MINERALS ─── -->
    <section>
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-8">
        <div class="bg-red-700 text-white text-xs font-bold px-3 py-1 rounded-full uppercase tracking-wide">Section 2</div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-stone-800">Rock & Mineral Resources</h2>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white rounded-2xl border border-stone-100 shadow-sm p-7 mb-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-stone-800 mb-4">What Minerals Are Found in Peru?</h3>
        <p class="text-stone-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
          The Andes mountain range, formed by millions of years of subduction and volcanic activity, created ideal conditions for metallic ore deposits. Peru is one of the world's top mineral-producing nations. It ranks among the <strong>top 5 global producers</strong> of copper, gold, silver, zinc, lead, and tin.
        </p>
        <div class="grid sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4 mb-4">
          <div class="bg-stone-50 rounded-xl p-4 border border-stone-200">
            <div class="flex justify-between items-start mb-1">
              <h4 class="font-bold text-stone-800">Copper</h4>
              <span class="text-xs bg-amber-100 text-amber-800 px-2 py-0.5 rounded-full font-medium">#2 in the world</span>
            </div>
            <p class="text-xs text-stone-500 mb-1">Location: Cusco, Apurímac, Moquegua</p>
            <p class="text-xs text-stone-600">Uses: Electrical wiring, electronics, construction</p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-stone-50 rounded-xl p-4 border border-stone-200">
            <div class="flex justify-between items-start mb-1">
              <h4 class="font-bold text-stone-800">Gold</h4>
              <span class="text-xs bg-amber-100 text-amber-800 px-2 py-0.5 rounded-full font-medium">#6 in the world</span>
            </div>
            <p class="text-xs text-stone-500 mb-1">Location: La Libertad, Cajamarca, Puno</p>
            <p class="text-xs text-stone-600">Uses: Jewelry, financial reserves, electronics</p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-stone-50 rounded-xl p-4 border border-stone-200">
            <div class="flex justify-between items-start mb-1">
              <h4 class="font-bold text-stone-800">Silver</h4>
              <span class="text-xs bg-amber-100 text-amber-800 px-2 py-0.5 rounded-full font-medium">#2 in the world</span>
            </div>
            <p class="text-xs text-stone-500 mb-1">Location: Pasco, Junín, Lima region</p>
            <p class="text-xs text-stone-600">Uses: Industrial applications, solar panels, jewelry</p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-stone-50 rounded-xl p-4 border border-stone-200">
            <div class="flex justify-between items-start mb-1">
              <h4 class="font-bold text-stone-800">Zinc</h4>
              <span class="text-xs bg-amber-100 text-amber-800 px-2 py-0.5 rounded-full font-medium">#3 in the world</span>
            </div>
            <p class="text-xs text-stone-500 mb-1">Location: Pasco (Cerro de Pasco)</p>
            <p class="text-xs text-stone-600">Uses: Steel galvanizing, batteries, alloys</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
        <div class="bg-white rounded-2xl border border-stone-100 shadow-sm p-6">
          <h3 class="font-bold text-stone-800 mb-3">Jobs & Exports</h3>
          <p class="text-stone-600 text-sm leading-relaxed mb-3">
            Mining employs over <strong>220,000 direct workers</strong> and more than 1 million indirectly. It accounts for approximately <strong>60% of Peru's total export earnings</strong>. Major export destinations include:
          </p>
          <ul class="space-y-1 text-sm text-stone-600">
            <li class="flex items-center gap-2"><span class="w-2 h-2 bg-red-500 rounded-full shrink-0"></span><span><strong>China</strong> — largest buyer of Peruvian copper and iron ore</span></li>
            <li class="flex items-center gap-2"><span class="w-2 h-2 bg-red-500 rounded-full shrink-0"></span><span><strong>United States</strong> — gold, zinc, lead</span></li>
            <li class="flex items-center gap-2"><span class="w-2 h-2 bg-red-500 rounded-full shrink-0"></span><span><strong>Japan & South Korea</strong> — copper and silver concentrates</span></li>
            <li class="flex items-center gap-2"><span class="w-2 h-2 bg-red-500 rounded-full shrink-0"></span><span><strong>European Union</strong> — precious metals and refined minerals</span></li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-white rounded-2xl border border-stone-100 shadow-sm p-6">
          <h3 class="font-bold text-stone-800 mb-3">Environmental & Social Impacts</h3>
          <p class="text-stone-600 text-sm leading-relaxed mb-3">
            While mining drives economic growth, it also creates serious environmental and social challenges:
          </p>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm text-stone-600">
            <li class="flex items-start gap-2"><span class="w-2 h-2 bg-amber-500 rounded-full shrink-0 mt-1.5"></span><span><strong>Water contamination</strong> — heavy metals from mining operations have polluted rivers in Cajamarca, Pasco, and the Amazon basin</span></li>
            <li class="flex items-start gap-2"><span class="w-2 h-2 bg-amber-500 rounded-full shrink-0 mt-1.5"></span><span><strong>Social conflict</strong> — over 60% of active social conflicts in Peru involve mining disputes between communities and companies</span></li>
            <li class="flex items-start gap-2"><span class="w-2 h-2 bg-amber-500 rounded-full shrink-0 mt-1.5"></span><span><strong>Deforestation</strong> — illegal gold mining in the Amazon (Madre de Dios) has destroyed over 95,000 hectares of rainforest</span></li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ─── SECTION 3: EARTHQUAKES ─── -->
    <section>
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-8">
        <div class="bg-red-700 text-white text-xs font-bold px-3 py-1 rounded-full uppercase tracking-wide">Section 3</div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-stone-800">Earthquakes</h2>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white rounded-2xl border border-stone-100 shadow-sm p-7 mb-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-stone-800 mb-5">Major Historical Earthquakes</h3>
        <div class="space-y-4">
          <div class="border-l-4 border-red-600 pl-5 py-2">
            <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-1">
              <span class="font-bold text-stone-800">1746 Lima-Callao Earthquake</span>
              <span class="text-xs bg-red-100 text-red-700 px-2 py-0.5 rounded-full">~8.0 Mw</span>
            </div>
            <p class="text-stone-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">Destroyed most of Lima and generated a massive tsunami that completely wiped out the port city of Callao. Estimated 5,000–6,000 deaths. One of the most destructive earthquakes in South American colonial history.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="border-l-4 border-red-600 pl-5 py-2">
            <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-1">
              <span class="font-bold text-stone-800">1970 Ancash Earthquake</span>
              <span class="text-xs bg-red-100 text-red-700 px-2 py-0.5 rounded-full">7.9 Mw</span>
            </div>
            <p class="text-stone-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">The deadliest earthquake in the Western Hemisphere in the 20th century. The earthquake triggered a massive landslide and debris avalanche from Mount Huascarán that buried the cities of Yungay and Ranrahirca, killing approximately <strong>70,000 people</strong>. Over 80,000 total deaths were recorded.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="border-l-4 border-red-600 pl-5 py-2">
            <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-1">
              <span class="font-bold text-stone-800">2007 Pisco Earthquake</span>
              <span class="text-xs bg-red-100 text-red-700 px-2 py-0.5 rounded-full">8.0 Mw</span>
            </div>
            <p class="text-stone-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">Struck the coast of the Ica Region, killing 519 people, injuring over 1,400, and leaving 58,000 families homeless. The city of Pisco was 80% destroyed. A small tsunami was also generated, reaching 5 meters at some points along the coast.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white rounded-2xl border border-stone-100 shadow-sm p-7">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-stone-800 mb-4">Government Preparedness Measures</h3>
        <p class="text-stone-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
          The Peruvian government has developed multiple systems to prepare citizens for seismic events:
        </p>
        <div class="grid sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
          <div class="bg-blue-50 rounded-xl p-4 border border-blue-100">
            <h4 class="font-semibold text-blue-800 text-sm mb-2">INDECI</h4>
            <p class="text-stone-600 text-xs leading-relaxed">The <em>Instituto Nacional de Defensa Civil</em> coordinates disaster prevention, response, and reconstruction. It conducts national earthquake drills (simulacros) twice a year involving millions of Peruvians.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-blue-50 rounded-xl p-4 border border-blue-100">
            <h4 class="font-semibold text-blue-800 text-sm mb-2">IGP Seismic Network</h4>
            <p class="text-stone-600 text-xs leading-relaxed">The <em>Instituto Geofísico del Perú</em> operates a national network of seismographs that monitors seismic activity in real time and issues public alerts.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-blue-50 rounded-xl p-4 border border-blue-100">
            <h4 class="font-semibold text-blue-800 text-sm mb-2">Tsunami Warning System</h4>
            <p class="text-stone-600 text-xs leading-relaxed">Peru participates in the Pacific Tsunami Warning Center (PTWC) network. Coastal cities have siren systems and designated evacuation routes marked with blue signage.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-blue-50 rounded-xl p-4 border border-blue-100">
            <h4 class="font-semibold text-blue-800 text-sm mb-2">Building Codes</h4>
            <p class="text-stone-600 text-xs leading-relaxed">Peru's <em>Norma Técnica E.030</em> sets seismic design standards for all new construction. Major cities have seismic microzonation maps that guide urban planning and infrastructure design.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ─── SECTION 4: MOUNTAIN RANGES ─── -->
    <section>
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-8">
        <div class="bg-red-700 text-white text-xs font-bold px-3 py-1 rounded-full uppercase tracking-wide">Section 4</div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-stone-800">Mountain Ranges</h2>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white rounded-2xl border border-stone-100 shadow-sm p-7 mb-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-stone-800 mb-4">The Andes — Cordillera de los Andes</h3>
        <p class="text-stone-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
          The <strong>Andes</strong> is the longest continental mountain range on Earth, stretching over <strong>7,000 km</strong> along the entire western coast of South America. In Peru, the Andes span the country from north to south and are divided into three parallel chains called <em>cordilleras</em>:
        </p>
        <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-4 mb-5">
          <div class="bg-stone-50 rounded-xl p-4 border border-stone-200">
            <h4 class="font-bold text-stone-800 text-sm mb-2">Cordillera Occidental</h4>
            <p class="text-stone-600 text-xs leading-relaxed">The western range, forming the continental divide. Contains most of Peru's active volcanoes. Average elevation 4,000–5,000 m.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-stone-50 rounded-xl p-4 border border-stone-200">
            <h4 class="font-bold text-stone-800 text-sm mb-2">Cordillera Central</h4>
            <p class="text-stone-600 text-xs leading-relaxed">The middle range, largely non-volcanic. Contains Huascarán (6,768 m) — the highest peak in Peru and the second highest in South America.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-stone-50 rounded-xl p-4 border border-stone-200">
            <h4 class="font-bold text-stone-800 text-sm mb-2">Cordillera Oriental</h4>
            <p class="text-stone-600 text-xs leading-relaxed">The eastern range, descending into the Amazon basin. Home to many archaeological sites including Machu Picchu (2,430 m).</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <h4 class="font-bold text-stone-700 mb-3">How Mountains Affect Peru</h4>
        <div class="grid sm:grid-cols-3 gap-4">
          <div class="bg-green-50 rounded-xl p-4 border border-green-100">
            <h5 class="font-semibold text-green-800 text-sm mb-1">Weather & Climate</h5>
            <p class="text-stone-600 text-xs leading-relaxed">The Andes act as a massive barrier, blocking moist Amazon air from reaching the coast — which is why Lima is a desert city despite being tropical in latitude. The mountains create over 30 distinct microclimates.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-green-50 rounded-xl p-4 border border-green-100">
            <h5 class="font-semibold text-green-800 text-sm mb-1">Water Supply</h5>
            <p class="text-stone-600 text-xs leading-relaxed">Andean glaciers and snowmelt feed all of Peru's major rivers. The Amazon River — the world's largest by volume — originates from an Andean spring in Arequipa. Over 70% of Peruvians depend on Andean water sources.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-green-50 rounded-xl p-4 border border-green-100">
            <h5 class="font-semibold text-green-800 text-sm mb-1">Culture & Trade</h5>
            <p class="text-stone-600 text-xs leading-relaxed">The Incas built their empire using mountain passes and the <em>Qhapaq Ñan</em> road system. Today the Andes still define cultural identity — highland communities (<em>serranos</em>) maintain distinct languages, agriculture (quinoa, potato, alpaca), and traditions.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ─── SECTION 5: VOLCANOES ─── -->
    <section>
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-8">
        <div class="bg-red-700 text-white text-xs font-bold px-3 py-1 rounded-full uppercase tracking-wide">Section 5</div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-stone-800">Volcanoes</h2>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white rounded-2xl border border-stone-100 shadow-sm p-7 mb-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-stone-800 mb-4">Peru's Major Volcanoes</h3>
        <p class="text-stone-600 leading-relaxed mb-5">
          Peru has <strong>84 identified volcanoes</strong>, concentrated in the southern Andes near Arequipa. All are <strong>composite volcanoes (stratovolcanoes)</strong> — tall, steep, cone-shaped mountains built from alternating layers of lava, ash, and pyroclastic material. They are the result of the subducting Nazca Plate melting and sending magma upward through the overlying crust.
        </p>
        <div class="space-y-4">
          <div class="flex flex-col sm:flex-row gap-4 bg-stone-50 rounded-xl p-5 border border-stone-200">
            <div class="sm:w-1/4">
              <h4 class="font-bold text-stone-800">El Misti</h4>
              <p class="text-xs text-stone-500">5,822 m · Arequipa</p>
              <span class="text-xs bg-yellow-100 text-yellow-800 px-2 py-0.5 rounded-full">Potentially Active</span>
            </div>
            <div class="sm:w-3/4">
              <p class="text-stone-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">Peru's most iconic volcano, overlooking the city of Arequipa (1 million residents). A composite stratovolcano with a nearly perfect cone. Last erupted in 1985 with minor ash emissions. Its proximity to Arequipa makes it one of the most dangerous volcanoes in South America. Scientists monitor it continuously for signs of renewed activity.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="flex flex-col sm:flex-row gap-4 bg-stone-50 rounded-xl p-5 border border-stone-200">
            <div class="sm:w-1/4">
              <h4 class="font-bold text-stone-800">Ubinas</h4>
              <p class="text-xs text-stone-500">5,672 m · Moquegua</p>
              <span class="text-xs bg-red-100 text-red-800 px-2 py-0.5 rounded-full">Most Active</span>
            </div>
            <div class="sm:w-3/4">
              <p class="text-stone-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">Peru's most historically active volcano, with over 24 recorded eruption periods since 1550. Had a major eruptive period from 2014–2017, releasing large ash columns and sulfur dioxide that forced evacuations of nearby communities and damaged local agriculture. An eruption in 2023 again put surrounding towns on alert.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="flex flex-col sm:flex-row gap-4 bg-stone-50 rounded-xl p-5 border border-stone-200">
            <div class="sm:w-1/4">
              <h4 class="font-bold text-stone-800">Sabancaya</h4>
              <p class="text-xs text-stone-500">5,976 m · Arequipa</p>
              <span class="text-xs bg-red-100 text-red-800 px-2 py-0.5 rounded-full">Currently Active</span>
            </div>
            <div class="sm:w-3/4">
              <p class="text-stone-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">One of the most active volcanoes in South America. Has been in near-continuous eruption since 2016, releasing ash plumes and high concentrations of sulfur dioxide daily. Sits between two other major volcanoes (Ampato and Hualca Hualca) and its activity threatens nearby communities and archaeological sites.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-5">
        <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-100 rounded-2xl p-5">
          <h4 class="font-bold text-amber-800 mb-2">Fertile Soil</h4>
          <p class="text-stone-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">Volcanic ash deposited over centuries has created some of the most fertile agricultural land in Peru. The Arequipa and Moquegua regions near active volcanoes produce rice, alfalfa, garlic, and onions thanks to nutrient-rich volcanic soils.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-100 rounded-2xl p-5">
          <h4 class="font-bold text-amber-800 mb-2">Tourism</h4>
          <p class="text-stone-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">El Misti and the Colca Canyon (formed by volcanic activity) attract thousands of tourists annually. The Colca Canyon — one of the world's deepest — was carved by the Colca River cutting through volcanic rock, and is home to the Andean condor.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-100 rounded-2xl p-5">
          <h4 class="font-bold text-amber-800 mb-2">Threats</h4>
          <p class="text-stone-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">Ash fall contaminates water supplies, damages crops, and closes airports. Lahars (volcanic mudflows) can travel down river valleys at deadly speeds. Peru's <em>Instituto Geofísico del Perú</em> (IGP) monitors all active volcanoes and issues color-coded alert levels.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ─── VIDEO PLACEHOLDER ─── -->
    <section>
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-6">
        <div class="bg-red-700 text-white text-xs font-bold px-3 py-1 rounded-full uppercase tracking-wide">Video</div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-stone-800">Watch: Peru's Geological Forces</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="bg-white rounded-2xl border border-stone-100 shadow-sm overflow-hidden">
        <div class="relative w-full" style="padding-bottom: 56.25%;">
          <iframe
            class="absolute inset-0 w-full h-full"
            src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/LlmSYB2nqP8"
            title="Earthquake in Peru"
            allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture"
            allowfullscreen
          ></iframe>
        </div>
        <div class="p-5">
          <p class="text-stone-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">This video documents real earthquake activity in Peru, illustrating the seismic forces generated by the subduction of the Nazca Plate beneath the South American Plate. Peru experiences thousands of earthquakes each year due to its position along the Pacific Ring of Fire.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ─── CITATIONS ─── -->
    <section class="bg-white rounded-2xl border border-stone-100 shadow-sm p-8">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-stone-800 mb-6">References (APA Format)</h2>
      <ul class="space-y-4 text-stone-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">
        <li><p>Geological Society of America. (2019). <em>Subduction zone geology of the central Andes</em>. GSA Bulletin.</p></li>
